This paper discusses the fundamentals of binary search trees and digital search trees, which are data structures commonly studied in computer science. Therefore, it is likely to belong to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. The paper also discusses probability generating functions, which are commonly studied in information theory (cs.IT) and combinatorics (cs.DM). Additionally, the paper discusses higher moments of search costs, which is a topic in computational complexity (cs.CC) and numerical analysis (cs.NA).
